### Notes

Just some necessary caveats and footnotes, because nothing is ever straightforward.

*   ^ The following countries are from 2020–24 data: Afghanistan, Eritrea, Lebanon, Palestine, Sri Lanka, Syria.
*   ^ The following countries are from 2022 data: San Marino and U.S. Virgin Islands.
*   ^ The following countries are from 2020–2022 data: Congo, San Marino, and U.S. Virgin Islands.
*   ^ IMF and CIA figures exclude [Taiwan](/Taiwan) and the [special administrative regions](/Special_administrative_regions_of_China) of [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong) and [Macau](/Macau). Because, apparently, some economic entities are more "country" than others, depending on who's counting.
*   ^ World Bank figures exclude the [special administrative regions](/Special_administrative_regions_of_China) of [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong) and [Macau](/Macau). Consistency is, as always, overrated.
*   ^ Figures exclude the [Republic of Crimea](/Republic_of_Crimea_(Russia)) and [Sevastopol](/Sevastopol). The political landscape always complicates the economic one.
*   ^ Includes [Western Sahara](/Western_Sahara).
*   ^ Referred to as "Burma". Because names are hard.
*   ^ Excludes data for [Abkhazia](/Abkhazia) and [South Ossetia](/South_Ossetia). More political complexities, more data exclusions.
*   ^ Data is for the area controlled by the Government of the [Republic of Cyprus](/Republic_of_Cyprus). A fragmented reality, reflected in fragmented data.
*   ^ Excludes data for [Transnistria](/Transnistria). Again, the political map doesn't always align with the economic one.
*   ^ Referred to as "West Bank and Gaza" in the IMF and World Bank reports.
*   ^ CIA registers 2 separate entries for Palestine: "West Bank" and "Gaza Strip". Figures for [West Bank](/West_Bank) include the [Gaza Strip](/Gaza_Strip) -- see "The World Factbook - West Bank". CIA.gov . 29 November 2022. Because granular data is sometimes less clear than it purports to be.
*   ^ Referred to as "Cabo Verde". Another name game.

